📚 Chapter 1: Matrices – Theorems & Topics

1️⃣ Definition of Matrix

A matrix is a rectangular arrangement of numbers (real or complex) in rows and columns.
Example:

A=[123456]A=\begin{bmatrix}1 & 2 & 3\\4 & 5 & 6\end{bmatrix}A=[14​25​36​]

This is a 2×32 \times 32×3 matrix (2 rows, 3 columns).

2️⃣ Types of Matrices

  • Row matrix – only one row.

  • Column matrix – only one column.

  • Square matrix – number of rows = number of columns.

  • Zero (Null) matrix – all elements are 0.

  • Diagonal matrix – all non-diagonal elements 0.

  • Scalar matrix – diagonal matrix with all diagonal elements equal.

  • Identity matrix III – diagonal elements = 1, others = 0.

  • Symmetric matrix – AT=AA^T = AAT=A.

  • Skew-symmetric matrix – AT=−AA^T = -AAT=−A.

3️⃣ Matrix Operations

  • Addition/Subtraction – same order matrices only; add corresponding elements.

  • Scalar Multiplication – multiply every element by scalar.

  • Multiplication of Matrices –
    If AAA is m×nm\times nm×n and BBB is n×pn\times pn×p,
    then ABABAB is m×pm\times pm×p with
    (AB)ij=∑aikbkj(AB)_{ij} = \sum a_{ik}b_{kj}(AB)ij​=∑aik​bkj​.

If A=[aij]A=[a_{ij}]A=[aij​], then AT=[aji]A^T=[a_{ji}]AT=[aji​] (rows become columns).

Theorems about Transpose:

  1. (A+B)T=AT+BT(A+B)^T = A^T + B^T(A+B)T=AT+BT

  2. (kA)T=kAT(kA)^T = kA^T(kA)T=kAT

  3. (AB)T=BTAT(AB)^T = B^T A^T(AB)T=BTAT

5️⃣ Determinants

Associated with square matrices only.
It’s a number calculated from elements of the matrix.

  • For 2×2: ∣abcd∣=ad−bc\begin{vmatrix}a&b\\c&d\end{vmatrix} = ad - bc​ac​bd​​=ad−bc

  • For 3×3: Use expansion by minors.

6️⃣ Minors & Cofactors

  • Minor of element aija_{ij}aij​: determinant obtained by deleting ith row & jth column.

  • Cofactor Cij=(−1)i+j×Minor of aijC_{ij} = (-1)^{i+j} \times \text{Minor of }a_{ij}Cij​=(−1)i+j×Minor of aij​.

Theorem 1:
If AAA and BBB are two matrices of the same order, then

(A+B)T=AT+BT(A + B)^T = A^T + B^T(A+B)T=AT+BT

This is the transpose-of-a-sum theorem.

📝 Statement

The transpose of the sum of two matrices is equal to the sum of their transposes.

📚 Explanation

If
A=[aij]A = [a_{ij}]A=[aij​] and B=[bij]B = [b_{ij}]B=[bij​] are both m×nm \times nm×n matrices,

then
A+B=[aij+bij]A + B = [a_{ij} + b_{ij}]A+B=[aij​+bij​] (element-wise addition).

Now the transpose of A+BA + BA+B is:

(A+B)T=[aji+bji](A+B)^T = [a_{ji}+b_{ji}](A+B)T=[aji​+bji​]

But
AT=[aji]A^T=[a_{ji}]AT=[aji​] and BT=[bji]B^T=[b_{ji}]BT=[bji​],

so
AT+BT=[aji]+[bji]=[aji+bji]A^T+B^T=[a_{ji}]+[b_{ji}]=[a_{ji}+b_{ji}]AT+BT=[aji​]+[bji​]=[aji​+bji​].

Thus

(A+B)T=AT+BT\boxed{(A+B)^T=A^T+B^T}(A+B)T=AT+BT​

🧠 Why it’s true (Intuition)

Transpose just flips rows and columns.
Adding two matrices first and then flipping = flipping each first and then adding.
The order doesn’t matter.

📌 Example

Let
A=[1234]A=\begin{bmatrix}1&2\\3&4\end{bmatrix}A=[13​24​],
B=[5678]B=\begin{bmatrix}5&6\\7&8\end{bmatrix}B=[57​68​]

Then
A+B=[681012]A+B=\begin{bmatrix}6&8\\10&12\end{bmatrix}A+B=[610​812​]

(A+B)T=[610812](A+B)^T=\begin{bmatrix}6&10\\8&12\end{bmatrix}(A+B)T=[68​1012​]

Now
AT=[1324]A^T=\begin{bmatrix}1&3\\2&4\end{bmatrix}AT=[12​34​],
BT=[5768]B^T=\begin{bmatrix}5&7\\6&8\end{bmatrix}BT=[56​78​]

AT+BT=[610812]A^T+B^T=\begin{bmatrix}6&10\\8&12\end{bmatrix}AT+BT=[68​1012​]

Both are same ✅

📝 Theorem 1 (Matrix–Vector Product as Linear Combination)

Let
A=[a11a12…a1na21a22…a2n⋮⋮⋱⋮am1am2…amn]A=\begin{bmatrix}a_{11}&a_{12}&\dots&a_{1n}\\a_{21}&a_{22}&\dots&a_{2n}\\\vdots&\vdots&\ddots&\vdots\\a_{m1}&a_{m2}&\dots&a_{mn}\end{bmatrix}A=​a11​a21​⋮am1​​a12​a22​⋮am2​​……⋱…​a1n​a2n​⋮amn​​​
be an m×nm \times nm×n matrix, and let
X⃗=[x1x2⋮xn]\vec X=\begin{bmatrix}x_1\\x_2\\\vdots\\x_n\end{bmatrix}X=​x1​x2​⋮xn​​​
be an n×1n\times 1n×1 column vector.

Then

AX⃗=x1[a11a21⋮am1]+x2[a12a22⋮am2]+⋯+xn[a1na2n⋮amn]A\vec X=x_1\begin{bmatrix}a_{11}\\a_{21}\\\vdots\\a_{m1}\end{bmatrix} +x_2\begin{bmatrix}a_{12}\\a_{22}\\\vdots\\a_{m2}\end{bmatrix} +\dots +x_n\begin{bmatrix}a_{1n}\\a_{2n}\\\vdots\\a_{mn}\end{bmatrix}AX=x1​​a11​a21​⋮am1​​​+x2​​a12​a22​⋮am2​​​+⋯+xn​​a1n​a2n​⋮amn​​​

In words:
Multiplying a matrix AAA by a column vector X⃗\vec XX gives a linear combination of the columns of AAA, where the coefficients are the entries of X⃗\vec XX (i.e. x1,x2,…,xnx_1,x_2,\dots,x_nx1​,x2​,…,xn​).

🔍 Proof Idea (why this works)

By definition of matrix multiplication:

AX⃗=[a11x1+a12x2+⋯+a1nxna21x1+a22x2+⋯+a2nxn⋮am1x1+am2x2+⋯+amnxn]A\vec X= \begin{bmatrix} a_{11}x_1+a_{12}x_2+\dots+a_{1n}x_n\\[4pt] a_{21}x_1+a_{22}x_2+\dots+a_{2n}x_n\\[4pt] \vdots\\[4pt] a_{m1}x_1+a_{m2}x_2+\dots+a_{mn}x_n \end{bmatrix}AX=​a11​x1​+a12​x2​+⋯+a1n​xn​a21​x1​+a22​x2​+⋯+a2n​xn​⋮am1​x1​+am2​x2​+⋯+amn​xn​​​

If you separate terms by x1,x2,…x_1,x_2,\dotsx1​,x2​,… you get:

x1[a11a21⋮am1]+x2[a12a22⋮am2]+⋯+xn[a1na2n⋮amn]x_1\begin{bmatrix}a_{11}\\a_{21}\\\vdots\\a_{m1}\end{bmatrix} +x_2\begin{bmatrix}a_{12}\\a_{22}\\\vdots\\a_{m2}\end{bmatrix} +\dots+x_n\begin{bmatrix}a_{1n}\\a_{2n}\\\vdots\\a_{mn}\end{bmatrix}x1​​a11​a21​⋮am1​​​+x2​​a12​a22​⋮am2​​​+⋯+xn​​a1n​a2n​⋮amn​​​

This is exactly a linear combination of the columns of AAA.

📌 Why this theorem matters

  • It gives a clear picture of what the matrix–vector product does geometrically:
    It “mixes” the columns of AAA using the coefficients from X⃗\vec XX.

  • It’s the basis for understanding span and column space in linear algebra.

  • It explains how systems of linear equations can be written compactly as AX⃗=b⃗A\vec X=\vec bAX=b.

🟩 1.4 Partition of Matrices

📚 Definition (Submatrix)

If we delete some (but not all) rows or columns from a matrix AAA, the remaining numbers form a submatrix of AAA.

Example:
A=[4123−3503−24−32]A=\begin{bmatrix}4&1&2&3\\-3&5&0&3\\-2&4&-3&2\end{bmatrix}A=​4−3−2​154​20−3​332​​

  • If you delete 3rd row and 3rd & 4th columns, you get
    [41−35]\begin{bmatrix}4&1\\-3&5\end{bmatrix}[4−3​15​] — a submatrix.

  • If you delete 1st column and 3rd row, you get
    [123503]\begin{bmatrix}1&2&3\\5&0&3\end{bmatrix}[15​20​33​].

  • If you delete 2nd row, you get
    [4123−24−32]\begin{bmatrix}4&1&2&3\\-2&4&-3&2\end{bmatrix}[4−2​14​2−3​32​].

📚 Definition (Partition)

If we draw horizontal and vertical lines inside a matrix to split it into blocks, we get a partition of AAA. Each block is itself a submatrix.

Example from your book:

A=[0−13−241−10−3142]A=\begin{bmatrix}0&-1&3&-2\\4&1&-1&0\\-3&1&4&2\end{bmatrix}A=​04−3​−111​3−14​−202​​

Draw two vertical lines and one horizontal line to get:

A=[P11P12P13P21P22P23]A=\begin{bmatrix} P_{11}&P_{12}&P_{13}\\ P_{21}&P_{22}&P_{23} \end{bmatrix}A=[P11​P21​​P12​P22​​P13​P23​​]

where

  • P11=[04]P_{11}=\begin{bmatrix}0\\4\end{bmatrix}P11​=[04​],

  • P12=[−11]P_{12}=\begin{bmatrix}-1\\1\end{bmatrix}P12​=[−11​],

  • P13=[3−1]P_{13}=\begin{bmatrix}3\\-1\end{bmatrix}P13​=[3−1​],

  • P21=[−3]P_{21}=\begin{bmatrix}-3\end{bmatrix}P21​=[−3​],

  • P22=[14]P_{22}=\begin{bmatrix}1&4\end{bmatrix}P22​=[1​4​],

  • P23=[2]P_{23}=\begin{bmatrix}2\end{bmatrix}P23​=[2​].

Thus each PijP_{ij}Pij​ is a submatrix of AAA.

📌 Notes on Partitioned Matrices

  • If AAA and BBB are partitioned in the same way, then:

    • A+BA+BA+B is formed by adding the corresponding blocks Aij+BijA_{ij}+B_{ij}Aij​+Bij​.

    • kAkAkA is formed by multiplying each block by kkk.

  • If AAA and BBB are partitioned compatibly for multiplication, we can define their product blockwise. That is exactly what Theorem 2 formalizes.

🟩 Theorem 2 (Multiplication of Block Matrices)

📝 Statement

Let AAA be an m×nm\times nm×n matrix and BBB be an n×pn\times pn×p matrix.
Suppose AAA is partitioned horizontally into blocks A1jA_{1j}A1j​ and BBB vertically into blocks Bj1B_{j1}Bj1​ compatibly, then the product ABABAB can be computed as a block matrix with blocks given by the usual summation:

AB=[A11A12…A1k⋮⋮⋱⋮Ar1Ar2…Ark][B11…B1s⋮⋱⋮Bk1…Bks]AB=\begin{bmatrix}A_{11}&A_{12}&\dots&A_{1k}\\\vdots&\vdots&\ddots&\vdots\\A_{r1}&A_{r2}&\dots&A_{rk}\end{bmatrix} \begin{bmatrix}B_{11}&\dots&B_{1s}\\\vdots&\ddots&\vdots\\B_{k1}&\dots&B_{ks}\end{bmatrix}AB=​A11​⋮Ar1​​A12​⋮Ar2​​…⋱…​A1k​⋮Ark​​​​B11​⋮Bk1​​…⋱…​B1s​⋮Bks​​​

Then each block CijC_{ij}Cij​ of C=ABC=ABC=AB is

Cij=Ai1B1j+Ai2B2j+⋯+AikBkjC_{ij}=A_{i1}B_{1j}+A_{i2}B_{2j}+\dots+A_{ik}B_{kj}Cij​=Ai1​B1j​+Ai2​B2j​+⋯+Aik​Bkj​

— just like normal matrix multiplication, but at the block level.

📌 Proof Sketch

Because each block multiplication and addition is just ordinary multiplication/addition of submatrices, we can expand ABABAB row-by-column in blocks. The compatibility condition ensures the sizes match.

📌 Standard Example (like on your next page)

Let

A=[A11A12A21A22]A=\begin{bmatrix}A_{11}&A_{12}\\A_{21}&A_{22}\end{bmatrix}A=[A11​A21​​A12​A22​​],
B=[B11B12B21B22]B=\begin{bmatrix}B_{11}&B_{12}\\B_{21}&B_{22}\end{bmatrix}B=[B11​B21​​B12​B22​​]

where blocks are such that products make sense. Then

AB=[A11B11+A12B21A11B12+A12B22A21B11+A22B21A21B12+A22B22]AB=\begin{bmatrix} A_{11}B_{11}+A_{12}B_{21}&A_{11}B_{12}+A_{12}B_{22}\\ A_{21}B_{11}+A_{22}B_{21}&A_{21}B_{12}+A_{22}B_{22} \end{bmatrix}AB=[A11​B11​+A12​B21​A21​B11​+A22​B21​​A11​B12​+A12​B22​A21​B12​+A22​B22​​]

Theorem 3: Row-wise (or Column-wise) Expansion of the Product ABABAB

Here’s exactly what it says and means:

🟩 Theorem 3 (Row Expansion of ABABAB)

📝 Statement

If AAA is an m×nm\times nm×n matrix and BBB is an n×pn\times pn×p matrix, then the product ABABAB can be written as a sum of row vectors of AAA multiplied by row blocks of BBB, i.e.

AB=[row1(A)row2(A)⋮rowm(A)]BAB=\begin{bmatrix}\text{row}_1(A)\\\text{row}_2(A)\\\vdots\\\text{row}_m(A)\end{bmatrix}BAB=​row1​(A)row2​(A)⋮rowm​(A)​​B

or, more concretely, if AAA has rows
r1,r2,…,rm\mathbf{r}_1,\mathbf{r}_2,\dots,\mathbf{r}_mr1​,r2​,…,rm​ (each 1×n1\times n1×n),
then the rows of ABABAB are:

Rowi(AB)=ri Bfor each i\text{Row}_i(AB)=\mathbf{r}_i\,B\quad \text{for each }iRowi​(AB)=ri​Bfor each i

That is, each row of ABABAB is obtained by multiplying the corresponding row of AAA with BBB.

🧠 What this means

Think of AAA as mmm separate row vectors:

A=[r1r2⋮rm]A=\begin{bmatrix}\mathbf{r}_1\\\mathbf{r}_2\\\vdots\\\mathbf{r}_m\end{bmatrix}A=​r1​r2​⋮rm​​​

Then multiply each row vector ri\mathbf{r}_iri​ by BBB (on the left, because ri\mathbf{r}_iri​ is 1×n1\times n1×n and BBB is n×pn\times pn×p), you get the iiith row of ABABAB.

So the product can be “expanded” row by row:

AB=[r1Br2B⋮rmB]AB=\begin{bmatrix}\mathbf{r}_1B\\\mathbf{r}_2B\\\vdots\\\mathbf{r}_mB\end{bmatrix}AB=​r1​Br2​B⋮rm​B​​

📚 Proof Sketch

By definition of matrix multiplication:

(AB)ij=∑k=1naikbkj(AB)_{ij}=\sum_{k=1}^{n}a_{ik}b_{kj}(AB)ij​=k=1∑n​aik​bkj​

But the iiith row of AAA is (ai1,ai2,…,ain)(a_{i1},a_{i2},\dots,a_{in})(ai1​,ai2​,…,ain​).
Multiply this row vector by BBB (which is n×pn\times pn×p), you get a 1×p1\times p1×p row whose jjjth entry is exactly ∑aikbkj\sum a_{ik}b_{kj}∑aik​bkj​.
Hence the iiith row of ABABAB= (ith row of AAA)×BBB.
Q.E.D.

📌 Why useful

It lets you compute ABABAB row-by-row instead of element-by-element.
It also shows clearly how each row of the result depends only on the corresponding row of AAA and all of BBB.

🧮 Example

🟩 Theorem 4: Properties of Matrix Addition

Let A,B,CA,B,CA,B,C be matrices of the same order (same rows & columns), and let OOO denote the zero matrix (all entries 0).
Then:

  1. Commutative Law:

    A+B=B+AA+B=B+AA+B=B+A

  2. Associative Law:

    A+(B+C)=(A+B)+CA+(B+C)=(A+B)+CA+(B+C)=(A+B)+C

  3. Existence of Additive Identity (Zero Matrix):

    A+O=O+A=AA+O=O+A=AA+O=O+A=A

  4. Existence of Additive Inverse (Negative of a Matrix):
    For each AAA there exists −A-A−A such that

    A+(−A)=(−A)+A=OA+(-A)=(-A)+A=OA+(−A)=(−A)+A=O

  5. Cancellation Law:
    If A+C=B+CA+C=B+CA+C=B+C then A=BA=BA=B.

  • Zero matrix: By definition 0+aij=aij+0=aij0+a_{ij}=a_{ij}+0=a_{ij}0+aij​=aij​+0=aij​ for each entry.

  • Negative matrix: Define −A-A−A by (−A)ij=−aij( -A)_{ij}=-a_{ij}(−A)ij​=−aij​; then aij+(−aij)=0a_{ij}+(-a_{ij})=0aij​+(−aij​)=0.

  • Cancellation: From aij+cij=bij+cija_{ij}+c_{ij}=b_{ij}+c_{ij}aij​+cij​=bij​+cij​ for each i,ji,ji,j, subtract cijc_{ij}cij​ to get aij=bija_{ij}=b_{ij}aij​=bij​.

🟩 Theorem 5: Properties of Matrix Multiplication

Let A,B,CA,B,CA,B,C be matrices such that the indicated products are defined.
Let kkk be a scalar (real or complex number).

Then the following properties hold:

1️⃣ Associative Law

If the sizes are such that A(BC)A(BC)A(BC) and (AB)C(AB)C(AB)C are defined, then

A(BC)=(AB)CA(BC)=(AB)CA(BC)=(AB)C

(You can multiply in either grouping order, the result is the same.)

2️⃣ Left & Right Distributive Laws

  • Left distributive:

    A(B+C)=AB+ACA(B+C)=AB+ACA(B+C)=AB+AC

    (provided BBB and CCC are of same order and products defined)

  • Right distributive:

    (A+B)C=AC+BC(A+B)C=AC+BC(A+B)C=AC+BC

(But note: you cannot mix both sides differently — order matters.)

3️⃣ Scalar Multiplication

For any scalar kkk:

k(AB)=(kA)B=A(kB)k(AB)=(kA)B=A(kB)k(AB)=(kA)B=A(kB)

(You can “pull” the scalar out to the left, or push it inside on either AAA or BBB.)

4️⃣ Identity Matrix Property

If III is an identity matrix of suitable order:

AI=AandIA=AAI=A \quad\text{and}\quad IA=AAI=AandIA=A

5️⃣ Non-commutativity

In general,

AB≠BAAB\ne BAAB=BA

(Matrix multiplication is not commutative; you can’t change the order unless special conditions hold.)

6️⃣ Zero Matrix Property

If OOO is a zero matrix of suitable order:

AO=OandOA=OAO=O \quad\text{and}\quad OA=OAO=OandOA=O

🟩 Theorem 6: Properties of Scalar Multiplication of Matrices

📝 Statement

If AAA and BBB are matrices of the same order and k,lk,lk,l are scalars (real or complex numbers), then:

  1. k(A+B)=kA+kBk(A+B)=kA+kBk(A+B)=kA+kB

  2. (k+l)A=kA+lA(k+l)A=kA+lA(k+l)A=kA+lA

  3. k(lA)=(kl)Ak(lA)=(kl)Ak(lA)=(kl)A

  4. 1⋅A=A1\cdot A=A1⋅A=A

📚 Meaning of Each Property

🔹 1. Distributive over Matrix Addition

Multiplying a sum of matrices by a scalar is the same as multiplying each matrix by the scalar separately and then adding:

k(A+B)=kA+kBk(A+B)=kA+kBk(A+B)=kA+kB

This is exactly like numbers: 2(3+4)=2⋅3+2⋅42(3+4)=2\cdot3+2\cdot42(3+4)=2⋅3+2⋅4.

🔹 2. Distributive over Scalar Addition

If you add two scalars first and then multiply a matrix by the result, it’s the same as adding the two separate scalar multiples:

(k+l)A=kA+lA(k+l)A=kA+lA(k+l)A=kA+lA

Again like numbers: (2+3)5=2⋅5+3⋅5(2+3)5=2\cdot5+3\cdot5(2+3)5=2⋅5+3⋅5.

🔹 3. Associative with Scalars

If you multiply a matrix by a scalar, then by another scalar, you can combine the scalars first:

k(lA)=(kl)Ak(lA)=(kl)Ak(lA)=(kl)A

Like numbers: 2(3⋅5)=6⋅52(3\cdot5)=6\cdot52(3⋅5)=6⋅5.

🔹 4. Identity Scalar

Multiplying by 1 does nothing:

1⋅A=A1\cdot A=A1⋅A=A

🧠 Proofs (Entry-wise)

We know scalar multiplication is defined entrywise:
(kA)ij=k(aij)(kA)_{ij}=k(a_{ij})(kA)ij​=k(aij​).

  1. For k(A+B)=kA+kBk(A+B)=kA+kBk(A+B)=kA+kB:
    Left side’s (i,j)(i,j)(i,j) entry:
    k(aij+bij)=kaij+kbijk(a_{ij}+b_{ij})=ka_{ij}+kb_{ij}k(aij​+bij​)=kaij​+kbij​.
    Right side’s (i,j)(i,j)(i,j) entry:
    (kA)ij+(kB)ij=kaij+kbij(kA)_{ij}+(kB)_{ij}=ka_{ij}+kb_{ij}(kA)ij​+(kB)ij​=kaij​+kbij​.
    They’re equal.

  2. For (k+l)A=kA+lA(k+l)A=kA+lA(k+l)A=kA+lA:
    Left side’s (i,j)(i,j)(i,j): (k+l)aij=kaij+laij(k+l)a_{ij}=ka_{ij}+la_{ij}(k+l)aij​=kaij​+laij​.
    Right side’s (i,j)(i,j)(i,j): (kA)ij+(lA)ij=kaij+laij(kA)_{ij}+(lA)_{ij}=ka_{ij}+la_{ij}(kA)ij​+(lA)ij​=kaij​+laij​.
    Equal.

  3. For k(lA)=(kl)Ak(lA)=(kl)Ak(lA)=(kl)A:
    Left side’s (i,j)(i,j)(i,j): k(laij)=(kl)aijk(la_{ij})=(kl)a_{ij}k(laij​)=(kl)aij​.
    Right side’s (i,j)(i,j)(i,j): (kl)Aij=(kl)aij(kl)A_{ij}=(kl)a_{ij}(kl)Aij​=(kl)aij​.
    Equal.

  4. For 1⋅A=A1\cdot A=A1⋅A=A:
    Left side’s (i,j)(i,j)(i,j): 1⋅aij=aij1\cdot a_{ij}=a_{ij}1⋅aij​=aij​.
    Right side’s (i,j)(i,j)(i,j): aija_{ij}aij​.
    Equal.

So all properties hold for each element of the matrix.

🟩 Theorem 7: Properties of Transpose of a Matrix

Let A,BA,BA,B be matrices of suitable orders and kkk be a scalar.
Then:

1️⃣ Transpose of a Transpose

(AT)T=A(A^T)^T=A(AT)T=A

(Flipping twice returns the original matrix.)

2️⃣ Transpose of a Sum

(A+B)T=AT+BT(A+B)^T=A^T+B^T(A+B)T=AT+BT

(Flipping after adding = flipping each then adding.)

3️⃣ Transpose of a Scalar Multiple

(kA)T=kAT(kA)^T=kA^T(kA)T=kAT

(A number can be pulled out.)

4️⃣ Transpose of a Product

(AB)T=BTAT(AB)^T=B^T A^T(AB)T=BTAT

(Order reverses when you transpose a product.)

📚 Proofs (Entry-wise)

  • (Aᵀ)ᵀ=A:
    If A=[aij]A=[a_{ij}]A=[aij​], then AT=[aji]A^T=[a_{ji}]AT=[aji​], then (AT)T=[aij](A^T)^T=[a_{ij}](AT)T=[aij​]=A.

  • (A+B)ᵀ=Aᵀ+Bᵀ:
    ((A+B)T)ij=(A+B)ji=aji+bji=(AT+BT)ij((A+B)^T)_{ij}=(A+B)_{ji}=a_{ji}+b_{ji}=(A^T+B^T)_{ij}((A+B)T)ij​=(A+B)ji​=aji​+bji​=(AT+BT)ij​.

  • (kA)ᵀ=kAᵀ:
    ((kA)T)ij=(kA)ji=k aji=(kAT)ij((kA)^T)_{ij}=(kA)_{ji}=k\,a_{ji}=(kA^T)_{ij}((kA)T)ij​=(kA)ji​=kaji​=(kAT)ij​.

  • (AB)ᵀ=BᵀAᵀ:
    ((AB)T)ij=(AB)ji=∑kajkbki=∑kbkiajk=(BTAT)ij((AB)^T)_{ij}=(AB)_{ji}=\sum_{k}a_{jk}b_{ki}=\sum_{k}b_{ki}a_{jk}=(B^T A^T)_{ij}((AB)T)ij​=(AB)ji​=∑k​ajk​bki​=∑k​bki​ajk​=(BTAT)ij​.

🟩 Theorem 8: Effect of an Elementary Row Operation on a Product

📝 Statement

Let AAA be an m×nm \times nm×n matrix and BBB be an n×pn \times pn×p matrix.
Let eee be any elementary row operation.
Then:

e(AB)=(eA)Be(AB)=(eA)Be(AB)=(eA)B

In words:
If you apply an elementary row operation eee to the product ABABAB, it’s the same as first applying eee to AAA and then multiplying the result by BBB.

📚 Why True

  • Elementary row operations act on the rows of a matrix.

  • In ABABAB, each row is a linear combination of rows of AAA; so changing rows of AAA before multiplication produces exactly the same change as doing it after the multiplication.

  • You cannot directly “row-operate” on BBB to affect ABABAB; the row operations on the product always correspond to operations on the prefactor AAA.

This is useful because it lets you simplify AAA while keeping BBB fixed when solving equations.

🧮 Quick Example

A=[1234],B=[56]A=\begin{bmatrix}1&2\\3&4\end{bmatrix},\quad B=\begin{bmatrix}5\\6\end{bmatrix}A=[13​24​],B=[56​]

AB=[1∗5+2∗63∗5+4∗6]=[1739]AB=\begin{bmatrix}1*5+2*6\\3*5+4*6\end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix}17\\39\end{bmatrix}AB=[1∗5+2∗63∗5+4∗6​]=[1739​]

Do row operation R1↔R2R_1\leftrightarrow R_2R1​↔R2​:

  • eA=[3412]eA=\begin{bmatrix}3&4\\1&2\end{bmatrix}eA=[31​42​]

  • (eA)B=[3∗5+4∗61∗5+2∗6]=[3917](eA)B=\begin{bmatrix}3*5+4*6\\1*5+2*6\end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix}39\\17\end{bmatrix}(eA)B=[3∗5+4∗61∗5+2∗6​]=[3917​]

Do row operation on ABABAB directly (swap rows): e(AB)=[3917]e(AB)=\begin{bmatrix}39\\17\end{bmatrix}e(AB)=[3917​] — same result ✅

🟩 Theorem 9: Elementary Matrix as a Tool for Row Operations

📝 Statement

Let EEE be the elementary matrix obtained by applying a certain row operation eee to the identity matrix ImI_mIm​.
If AAA is any m×nm\times nm×n matrix, then

EA=e(A)EA=e(A)EA=e(A)

That is, multiplying AAA on the left by the elementary matrix EEE gives the same result as performing the row operation eee directly on AAA.

📚 Why True

  • EEE is just ImI_mIm​ but with one row operation applied: E=e(Im)E=e(I_m)E=e(Im​).

  • Then EA=e(Im)AEA=e(I_m)AEA=e(Im​)A.
    But ImA=AI_mA=AIm​A=A, and applying eee to ImAI_mAIm​A is the same as applying it to AAA.
    So EA=e(A)EA=e(A)EA=e(A).

This is exactly the proof your book shows.

🧠 Why It’s Important

  • Every row operation can be represented as multiplication by an elementary matrix on the left.

  • This gives a nice algebraic way to describe Gaussian elimination and other procedures.

  • It also underpins how we compute inverses using sequences of elementary matrices.

🧮 Quick Example

Take A=[1234]A=\begin{bmatrix}1&2\\3&4\end{bmatrix}A=[13​24​] and let eee be “swap row 1 and row 2.”

The elementary matrix for this is E=[0110]E=\begin{bmatrix}0&1\\1&0\end{bmatrix}E=[01​10​] (this is I2I_2I2​ with rows swapped).

Then EA=[0110][1234]=[3412]EA=\begin{bmatrix}0&1\\1&0\end{bmatrix}\begin{bmatrix}1&2\\3&4\end{bmatrix}=\begin{bmatrix}3&4\\1&2\end{bmatrix}EA=[01​10​][13​24​]=[31​42​] — exactly what you get if you swap rows of AAA directly.

📍 Takeaway

  • Theorem 8: Performing an elementary row operation on ABABAB = performing it on AAA first, then multiplying by BBB.

  • Theorem 9: An elementary row operation can be represented by an elementary matrix EEE; multiplying AAA by EEE on the left does the same as the row operation.

Theorem 2 — Multiplication of block (partitioned) matrices

Statement.

Matrix multiplication sums over matching column/row indices. If you treat each block as a single “entry” (provided sizes match), the same summation gives the block entries.

Theorem 4 — Properties of matrix addition

Statement. (For matrices A,B,CA,B,CA,B,C of same size and zero matrix OOO.)

  1. A+B=B+AA+B=B+AA+B=B+A (commutative).

  2. A+(B+C)=(A+B)+CA+(B+C)=(A+B)+CA+(B+C)=(A+B)+C (associative).

  3. A+O=AA+O=AA+O=A (zero is additive identity).

  4. ∃ (−A)\exists\,(-A)∃(−A) s.t. A+(−A)=OA+(-A)=OA+(−A)=O (additive inverse).

  5. Cancellation: if A+C=B+CA+C=B+CA+C=B+C then A=BA=BA=B.

Why / proof idea.
All properties follow entrywise from the corresponding properties of real numbers: (A+B)ij=aij+bij(A+B)_{ij}=a_{ij}+b_{ij}(A+B)ij​=aij​+bij​, and number addition is commutative/associative etc.

Theorem 5 — Properties of matrix multiplication

Statement. (Given compatible sizes and scalar kkk.)

  1. Associative: A(BC)=(AB)CA(BC)=(AB)CA(BC)=(AB)C.

  2. Distributive: A(B+C)=AB+ACA(B+C)=AB+ACA(B+C)=AB+AC and (A+B)C=AC+BC(A+B)C=AC+BC(A+B)C=AC+BC.

  3. Scalar: k(AB)=(kA)B=A(kB)k(AB)=(kA)B=A(kB)k(AB)=(kA)B=A(kB).

Theorem 6 — Properties of scalar multiplication

Statement. (For same-size matrices A,BA,BA,B and scalars k,lk,lk,l.)

  1. k(A+B)=kA+kBk(A+B)=kA+kBk(A+B)=kA+kB.

  2. (k+l)A=kA+lA(k+l)A=kA+lA(k+l)A=kA+lA.

  3. k(lA)=(kl)Ak(lA)=(kl)Ak(lA)=(kl)A.

  4. 1⋅A=A1\cdot A=A1⋅A=A.

Why / proof idea.
Entrywise: (k(A+B))ij=k(aij+bij)=kaij+kbij=(kA+kB)ij(k(A+B))_{ij}=k(a_{ij}+b_{ij})=ka_{ij}+kb_{ij}=(kA+kB)_{ij}(k(A+B))ij​=k(aij​+bij​)=kaij​+kbij​=(kA+kB)ij​, etc.

Theorem 7 — Properties of transpose

Statement. (For matrices A,BA,BA,B and scalar kkk.)

  1. (AT)T=A(A^T)^T=A(AT)T=A.

  2. (A+B)T=AT+BT(A+B)^T=A^T+B^T(A+B)T=AT+BT.

  3. (kA)T=kAT(kA)^T=kA^T(kA)T=kAT.

  4. (AB)T=BTAT(AB)^T=B^T A^T(AB)T=BTAT.

Why / proof idea.
Transpose flips indices: (AT)ij=aji(A^T)_{ij}=a_{ji}(AT)ij​=aji​. Apply definitions and rearrange indices (for product, reverse order of multiplication).

Theorem 8 — Elementary row operation on product: e(AB)=(eA)Be(AB)=(eA)Be(AB)=(eA)B

Statement.
Let AAA be m×nm\times nm×n, BBB be n×pn\times pn×p. If eee is an elementary row operation (swap rows, multiply a row by a nonzero scalar, add a multiple of one row to another), then applying eee to the product is the same as applying eee to the left factor AAA and then multiplying:

e(AB)=(eA)B.e(AB)=(eA)B.e(AB)=(eA)B.

Why / proof idea.
Elementary row operations change rows. Rows of ABABAB depend only on corresponding rows of AAA (Theorem 3). So changing rows of AAA first produces exactly the same change in ABABAB.

Textbook example (from your PDF).
The PDF shows examples like performing R1+(−2)R3R_1 + (-2)R_3R1​+(−2)R3​ on AAA gives E1AE_1AE1​A, performing 3R23R_23R2​ on AAA gives E2AE_2AE2​A, and performing R23R_{23}R23​ on AAA gives E3AE_3AE3​A. It states if eee is an elementary row operation then e(AB)=(eA)Be(AB)=(eA)Be(AB)=(eA)B.

Simple numeric example (worked).
Let
A=[1234]A=\begin{bmatrix}1&2\\3&4\end{bmatrix}A=[13​24​], B=[56]B=\begin{bmatrix}5\\6\end{bmatrix}B=[56​].

  • Let eee be the row-swap operation R1↔R2R_1\leftrightarrow R_2R1​↔R2​. Applying eee to ABABAB yields [3917]\begin{bmatrix}39\\17\end{bmatrix}[3917​].

  • They match, showing e(AB)=(eA)Be(AB)=(eA)Be(AB)=(eA)B.

Theorem 9 — Elementary matrices represent row operations: EA=e(A)EA=e(A)EA=e(A)

Statement.
If EEE is the elementary matrix obtained by performing row operation eee on the identity ImI_mIm​, then for any m×nm\times nm×n matrix AAA,

EA=e(A).EA = e(A).EA=e(A).

So left-multiplication by EEE performs the row operation eee on AAA.

Why / proof idea.
A=ImAA = I_m AA=Im​A. Apply eee: e(A)=e(ImA)=e(Im)A=EAe(A)=e(I_mA)=e(I_m)A=EAe(A)=e(Im​A)=e(Im​)A=EA, and e(Im)e(I_m)e(Im​) is by definition the elementary matrix EEE.

Textbook example (from your PDF).
The book points out precisely: if elementary matrix EEE results from performing row operation eee on ImI_mIm​, then EAEAEA is the matrix obtained when the same row operation is performed on AAA. It also shows specific elementary matrices arising from sample row operations.

Extra useful facts from these theorems

  • Elementary matrices are always invertible; the inverse is the elementary matrix corresponding to the inverse row op (swap is its own inverse, scaling by kkk inverse is scaling by 1/k1/k1/k, adding λλλ times row jjj invert by adding −λ-λ−λ times row jjj).

  • Gaussian elimination can be written as product of elementary matrices: if UUU is the row-reduced form of AAA, then Er⋯E2E1A=UE_r\cdots E_2 E_1 A = UEr​⋯E2​E1​A=U.
